2026-04-10 | Minimum Distance of Equal Triplet

Question:
•	You are given an array nums.  
•	A valid (good) triplet:
		nums[i] == nums[j] == nums[k]  
		i, j, k are distinct  

•	Distance:
		|i - j| + |j - k| + |k - i|  

•	Goal:
		find minimum possible distance among all such triplets.

	Key Insight
For sorted indices i < j < k:
		distance = (j-i) + (k-j) + (k-i)
				 = 2*(k - i)

So:
→ minimize (k - i)

Meaning:
just pick **closest 3 occurrences** of same number.

	Approach
1.	Group indices by value using hashmap:
		value → list of indices  

2.	For each value:
		if size < 3 → skip  

3.	Check every consecutive triplet:
		indices[i], indices[i+1], indices[i+2]  

		distance = 2 * (indices[i+2] - indices[i])

4.	Take minimum over all values  

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int minimumDistance(vector<int>& nums) {

        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> mp;

        int n = nums.size();

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            mp[nums[i]].push_back(i);
        }

        int ans = INT_MAX;

        for(auto &p : mp){

            auto &v = p.second;

            if(v.size() < 3) continue;

            for(int i = 0; i + 2 < v.size(); i++){
                int dist = 2 * (v[i+2] - v[i]);
                ans = min(ans, dist);
            }
        }

        return ans == INT_MAX ? -1 : ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
The formula simplifies drastically:
		distance = 2 × (k - i)

So we only need to find:
		three closest occurrences of same value  

This reduces problem to a simple **sliding window on indices**.
